comments.body: What is the difference between Pacific Poison Ivy and Western Poison Ivy?

T. diversilobum has leaflets that are roughly oval in overall shape, and always conspicuously lobed. It's also only known from east of the Cascades around the Columbia Gorge, and from one spot along the Snake (I was going to examine that specimen once, but ran out of time). T. rydbergii is very common on colluvial soils in canyons east of the Cascades, and has leaflets that taper gradually to a distinct tip, with or without small lobes.
Thank you! I see the difference now.

comments.body: i suppose rydbergii is also possible, any thoughts @erikamitchell ? I didn't know poison ivy was in places this cold.

I would suggest T. rydbergii based on the way the leaves seem to be at the ends of the stems. T. radicans seems to have more leaves along the stems. This photo also doesn't show any indication of a viney habitat or aerial roots.

identifications.body: yeah it was in an odd clump. no signs of viney-ness. odd habitat, kind of a seep and of course very cold area

comments.body: based on form or are there leaf characteristics? i forget

I was basing it mainly on form--this looks low shrubby rather than viney. As for leaves, Go Botany says " Stems straggling to erect, without aerial roots; leaves tending to be clustered near the tip of the stem, often slightly folded" for T. rydbergii and "leaves alternately scattered throughout the stem, usually flat" for T. radicans. With leaves just at the tops of the stems, this seemed a better fit for T. rydbergii to me.
it seems right, they are foldy, and also isn't rydergii more likely in wetlands? Looks like you were around Chickering Fen

identifications.body: Toxicodendron radicans is a high-climbing vine with aerial roots. The low shrub form of poison-ivy is T. rydbergii. T. radicans does occur on Grenadier Island and elsewhere along the St. Lawrence River in the 1000 Islands, as well as at Charleston Lake.

non_owner_ids.body: Toxicodendron radicans is a high-climbing vine with aerial roots. The low shrub form of poison-ivy is T. rydbergii. T. radicans does occur on Grenadier Island and elsewhere along the St. Lawrence River in the 1000 Islands, as well as at Charleston Lake.

comments.body: I know this is common on the park, but what do you see here that indicates rydbergii?

Its not clear from the photo and there are probably better patches nearby I should have taken a photo of, but this is the lack of aerial roots and its more shrub-like (less vine-like).  Most of it at PISP is on the beachs and backdunes, T. radicans is present, but really climbs (competitive exclusion?).

results.description: Does poison Ivy make it out west to Colorado?

default_photo.attribution: (c) Dan Mullen, some rights reserved (CC BY-NC-ND)

comments.body: I checked a USDA range map and it does not show poison ivy in Colorado. Fragrant sumac looks very much like poison ivy, so much so that even when I know the plant I am looking at is fragrant sumac, I can't bring myself to touch it. I checked  a USDA range map for fragrant sumac and it does not show it in Colorado. Either the range maps are wrong or this is box elder.
That would be embarrassing - it was a low ground-cover, definitely got my Toxicodendron spider senses tingling, but I have to admit I didn't spend to much time looking at it - just snapped a picture.

I don't think it is fragrant sumac, due to the long petiole after the leaflets split off.  It sure looks like poison ivy, I don't think poison oak goes that far east.

I don't usually see Box Elder with leaves like that either.  Was it a tree/upright shrub?
This looks a lot like Toxicodendron rydbergii, its similar to T. radicans but the gestalt of the plant in the photo seems to be more like what I've experienced in the field.
